\title{conjointmatchups: the data grammar of forced-choice conjoint experiments}
\description{
Forced-choice (paired) conjoint data has a fundamental duality. Each choice
task is at once two \emph{profile} rows (long form, natural for describing
attributes) and one \emph{task} row with per-profile columns (wide form, natural
for modeling the binary choice). conjointmatchups provides a lossless pivot
between these two representations (\code{\link[=as_tasks]{as_tasks()}}, \code{\link[=as_profiles]{as_profiles()}}) and a way to
extract \emph{matchups} (\code{\link[=get_matchups]{get_matchups()}}): the subset of tasks realizing a
specified contrast between the two profiles, returned with a clean binary
outcome that is ready to hand to any estimator.
}
\details{
The package deliberately does not re-implement AMCE or marginal-means
estimation (see 'cregg', 'cjoint', 'projoint', 'factorEx'). It produces the
analysis-ready datasets those tools consume, and underlies the Average Feature
Choice Probability (AFCP) estimand. A thin \code{\link[=afcp]{afcp()}} convenience closes the
loop for the AFCP workflow.
}
